How can you use Go code to simulate the crossing of a bridge by 100 people with varying speeds and limited flashlights, in order to find the most efficient way to get everyone across?
Here is the code:
package main
import (
    "fmt"
    "math/rand"
    "time"
)
type person struct {
    name   string
    speed  int
    crossed bool
}
type bridge struct {
    flashlight bool
    people     []*person
}
func (b *bridge) cross(p1 *person, p2 *person) {
    if !b.flashlight {
        b.flashlight = true
        fmt.Printf("%s and %s cross the bridge\n", p1.name, p2.name)
        p1.crossed = true
        p2.crossed = true
        b.flashlight = false
    }
}
func main() {
    rand.Seed(time.Now().UnixNano())
    people := make([]*person, 100)
    for i := range people {
        people[i] = &person{
            name:  fmt.Sprintf("Person %d", i+1),
            speed: rand.Intn(10) + 1, // random speed between 1 and 10
        }
    }
    var fastest *person
    for _, p := range people {
        if fastest == nil || p.speed < fastest.speed {
            fastest = p
        }
    }
    bridge := &bridge{
        flashlight: false,
        people:     people,
    }
    fmt.Printf("%s has the flashlight\n", fastest.name)
    for {
        // find the two fastest people who haven't crossed yet
        var p1, p2 *person
        for _, p := range people {
            if !p.crossed && (p1 == nil || p.speed < p1.speed) {
                p2 = p1
                p1 = p
            } else if !p.crossed && (p2 == nil || p.speed < p2.speed) {
                p2 = p
            }
        }
        // if there are no more people to cross, we're done
        if p1 == nil {
            break
        }
        // cross the bridge
        bridge.cross(p1, p2)
    }
    fmt.Println("Everyone has crossed the bridge!")
} 
How can you modify this code to consider the limited number of flashlights and the fact that two people without a flashlight cannot cross together? How can you use your leadership skills to optimize the crossing strategy and minimize delays caused by people having to return to the starting point?

To modify the code to consider the limited number of flashlights and the fact that two people without a flashlight cannot cross together, we can add a variable to keep track of the number of flashlights available and modify the `cross` function to only allow crossing if at least one person has a flashlight. Additionally, we can modify the `main` function to keep track of the number of people on each side of the bridge and only allow crossing if there is at least one person on the starting side with a flashlight.
Here's the modified code:
```
package main
import (
    "fmt"
    "math/rand"
    "time"
)
type person struct {
    name    string
    speed   int
    crossed bool
}
type bridge struct {
    flashlightCount int
