Yes, it is possible to load an external native library (.so file) during runtime in an Android app. You can use the `System.loadLibrary()` method to load the library dynamically.

Here are the basic steps to load an external native library in an Android app:

1. Store the native library (.so file) in a directory that is accessible by your app. Typically, this would be in the app's local data directory (/data/data/<package\_name>/lib/).
2. In your app's Java code, call the `System.loadLibrary()` method, passing in the name of the library without the "lib" prefix and the ".so" extension. For example, if your library is named "libnative.so", you would call `System.loadLibrary("native")`.

Here's an example code snippet that demonstrates loading an external native library in an Android app:
```java
public class MainActivity extends AppCompatActivity {
    static {
        System.loadLibrary("native");
    }
    // ...
}
```
In this example, the library named "libnative.so" would need to be placed in the appropriate directory (/data/data/<package\_name>/lib/) for the app to be able to load it.

Note that loading external native libraries dynamically can pose a security risk, so make sure that you only load libraries that you trust and that have been verified to be safe.

The static block of code you see in the `MainActivity` class is executed when the class is loaded by the JVM. In this case, the static block loads the native library using the `System.loadLibrary()` method.

When the `MainActivity` class is first referenced by your Android app (typically when the activity is launched), the JVM loads the class and executes any static blocks of code in the class. This is when the native library is loaded into the app's memory.

Once the library is loaded, you can access its functions from your Java code using the Java Native Interface (JNI). You would typically define a Java method that corresponds to each native function you want to call, and use JNI to call the corresponding native function.

Here's an example of how you might define a Java method that calls a native function:
```java
public class MainActivity extends AppCompatActivity {
    static {
        System.loadLibrary("native");
    }

    // Define a Java method that corresponds to a native function
    public native void doSomethingNative();

    // Call the native method from your Java code
    public void doSomething() {
        doSomethingNative();
    }
}
```
In this example, the `doSomethingNative()` method is defined as a native method, which means that it is implemented in the native code (i.e., in the native library). You can then call this method from your Java code by simply invoking the `doSomething()` method. When the `doSomethingNative()` method is called, the JVM uses JNI to execute the corresponding native function in the native library.

Yes, that's correct! You can create a button in your app's user interface, and when the user clicks the button, your app can call the `doSomething()` method (or any other method that uses the loaded native library).

Here's an example of how you might create a button in your app's layout XML file:
```xml
<Button
    android:id="@+id/loadLibraryButton"
    android:layout_width="wrap_content"
    android:layout_height="wrap_content"
    android:text="Load Native Library"
    android:onClick="onLoadLibraryClick" />
```
In this example, the `android:onClick` attribute is set to "onLoadLibraryClick", which specifies the name of the method that should be called when the button is clicked.

Next, you can define the `onLoadLibraryClick()` method in your `MainActivity` class:
```java
public class MainActivity extends AppCompatActivity {
    static {
        System.loadLibrary("native");
    }

    // Define a method that is called when the "Load Native Library" button is clicked
    public void onLoadLibraryClick(View view) {
        // Call the "doSomething()" method to load the native library and perform some action
        doSomething();
    }

    // Define a native method that is implemented in the native library
    public native void doSomething();
}
```
In this example, the `onLoadLibraryClick()` method is called when the "Load Native Library" button is clicked. This method simply calls the `doSomething()` method, which loads the native library and performs some action.

Note that you'll need to replace the `doSomething()` method with your own method that uses the loaded native library. The `doSomething()` method in this example is simply a placeholder for demonstration purposes.

Yes, if you are using Unity game engine, you can place a button in your game and use it to load an external native library in the same way as you would in a native Android app.

Here's an example of how you might load a native library in Unity:

1. First, you need to make sure that the native library (.so file) is included in your Unity project. You can do this by placing the library in the appropriate directory in your project's Assets folder. For example, if your library is named "libnative.so", you would place it in the Assets/Plugins/Android directory.
2. Next, you need to define a C# method in your Unity script that will call the native method in the library. This method should be decorated with the `DllImport` attribute to specify the name of the library and the name of the native method. Here's an example:
```csharp
using System.Runtime.InteropServices;

public class MyScript : MonoBehaviour
{
    [DllImport("native")]
    private static extern void doSomethingNative();

    public void doSomething()
    {
        doSomethingNative();
    }
}
