The Kalman filter is a mathematical method for estimating the state of a system from noisy measurements. It is a recursive algorithm that uses Bayesian estimation to compute the state of the system at each time step, based on the previous state and the current measurements. The algorithm can be written in pseudo-code as follows:
```
\begin{algorithmic}
\State $x_k = \mathbf{E}[x_k \mid z_{1:k-1}]$ \Comment{Predict state based on previous measurements}
\State $P_k = \mathbf{E}[(x_k-\hat{x}_k)(x_k-\hat{x}_k)^\top \mid z_{1:k-1}]$ \Comment{Predict covariance of state}
\State $K_k = P_kH_k^\top(H_kP_kH_k^\top+R)^{-1}$ \Comment{Compute Kalman gain}
\State $x_k = \hat{x}_k+K_k(z_k-H_k\hat{x}_k)$ \Comment{Update state estimate}
\State $P_k = (I-K_kH_k)P_k$ \Comment{Update covariance of state estimate}
\end{algorithmic}
```
In this code, $x\_k$ represents the state of the system at time $k$, $z\_k$ represents the measurement at time $k$, $\hat{x}\_k$ is the predicted state, $P\_k$ is the predicted covariance of the state, $K\_k$ is the Kalman gain, $H\_k$ is the measurement matrix, and $R$ is the measurement noise covariance matrix. The algorithm iterates over each time step, updating the state estimate and its covariance based on the current measurement.

It is important to note that the Kalman filter assumes a linear system and Gaussian noise, so it may not be applicable to all systems or measurement scenarios. Additionally, the accuracy of the algorithm depends on the quality of the initial state estimate and the values of the covariance matrices.

