Bicep is a new language for defining Azure infrastructure, and it provides a simpler and more declarative way to write Azure Resource Manager (ARM) templates. Bicep templates are compiled to ARM templates, so you can use them to deploy the same Azure resources that you can deploy with ARM templates.

Here is an example of what the Bicep file might look like for the "Hello, World" app example:
```
// Define a new resource group
resourceGroup exampleRG {
  name     = 'example-resource-group'
  location = 'East US'
}

// Define a new app service plan
appServicePlan exampleASP {
  name                = 'example-app-service-plan'
  location            = exampleRG.location
  resourceGroup       = exampleRG
  sku                 = { tier: 'Basic', size: 'B1' }
}

// Define a new web app
webApp exampleWebApp {
  name                = 'example-web-app'
  location            = exampleRG.location
  resourceGroup       = exampleRG
  appServicePlan      = exampleASP
  appSettings         = { 'WEBSITE_NODE_DEFAULT_VERSION' = '10.14' }
}
```
This Bicep file defines the same resources as the Terraform configuration file and ARM template, including a resource group, an App Service plan, and a web app. It also includes the "WEBSITE\_NODE\_DEFAULT\_VERSION" app setting that was specified in the other examples.

To deploy this Bicep file to Azure, you can use the `bicep` command-line tool to compile the file to an ARM template, and then use the Azure Portal, Azure PowerShell, Azure CLI, or any other method that you prefer to deploy the ARM template.

Here is an example of how you can use the `bicep` command-line tool to compile the Bicep file to an ARM template:
```
# Install the `bicep` command-line tool
npm install -g bicep

# Compile the Bicep file to an ARM template
bicep build hello-world.bicep
```
This will generate an ARM template named `hello-world.json` that can be deployed to Azure using the same methods as an ARM template that was authored directly in JSON.

Note: This is just a simple example to illustrate how to use Bicep to define Azure resources. In a real-world scenario, you may want to include additional configuration options, such as deploying the app code from a source code repository, configuring HTTPS, or enabling monitoring and logging.

